demand vs supply driven innovations us and swedish experiences in academic entrepreneurship siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected banner home publications profile display demand vs supply driven innovations us and swedish experiences in academic entrepreneurship type siepr discussion paper 00 035 author s brent goldfarb magnus henrekson nathan rosenberg published 02 1 01 download pdf abstract measured by per capita publication measures sweden is an academic powerhouse hence its inability to commercialize on these accomplishments is a puzzle this paper attributes this failure to the top down nature of swedish policies aimed at commercializing these innovations as well as an academic environment that discourages academics from actively participating in the commercialization of their ideas this sits in stark contrast to the us institutional setting that is characterized by competition between universities for research funds and research personnel which in turn has led to significant academic freedoms to interact with industry particularly by founding new firms we conclude that the technocratic supply driven nature of attempts to exploit academic output in sweden has been markedly less successful than the demand driven market institutions in the us stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
